Fig. 4
 shows the mechanism of PL quenching [30] of N-CDs by Fe3+. Under UV excitation, the N-CDs exhibit bright blue light in CF. With the increase of CF processing time in the machine tool, the concentration of Fe3+ increases, resulting in the decrease of PL intensity of N-CDs. To verify the applicability of N-CDs for Fe3+ detection in CF, 10 μM, 20 μM, 40 μM and 80 μM Fe3+ were added to the CF solution, respectively. More importantly, we tested the CF obtained from Frank Lubrication Technology (Taizhou) Co., Ltd. (Table 3
), which had been used for machining iron workpieces for 150 and 600 h respectively. The results showed that the Fe3+ concentrations of the two CFs were within the detection range of the N-CDs probe and were consistent with the results of ICP-OES. As shown in Table. 3, the standard deviation (RSD) for the detection of Fe3+ concentration in CF samples was less than 5.0 %, and the recoveries were between 99 % and 102 %. In summary, it is feasible to use N-CDs to detect the concentration of Fe3+ to predict the service life of CF.
